x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">House members are o=
n a hot streak in the primaries. Only <i>one</i> federal incumbent has lost=
 this cycle: Alabama=E2=80=99s <b>Jerry Carl</b>, who fell to fellow congre=
ssman <b>Barry Moore</b> after the courts redrew their respective districts=
, leading to the member vs. member showdown. But beginning Tuesday and thro=
ughout the summer, more than a dozen House incumbents will face serious pri=
mary challenges. (Senators, for their part, seem to be in the clear.)<br/><=
br/>On the Republican side, the battle lines have mostly been drawn around =
who did, and did not, support <b>Kevin McCarthy</b> when he was ousted from=
 the speakership. On the Democratic side, the dividing line is all about Is=
rael. This rundown is based on television ad spending, candidate fundraisin=
g, outside group spending, and of course, plenty of inside chatter. <br/><b=
r/><ul style=3D"margin:0;color:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;marg=
in-top:0;margin-bottom:0;list-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet">=
<li><i>McCarthy=E2=80=99s vendetta</i>: McCarthy is out for blood. The supe=
r PAC run by his longtime lieutenant, <b>Brian O. Walsh</b>, is spending bi=
g against two Republican members who voted to oust him: South Carolina=E2=
=80=99s <b>Nancy Mace</b> and Virginia=E2=80=99s <b>Bob Good</b>. Both Mace=
 and Good, however, are getting help from conservative groups. The consensu=
s is that Mace is probably in better shape than Good; his primary will take=
 place on June 18, and Mace=E2=80=99s on June 8. Two other anti-McCarthy in=
cumbents are also in the barrel: Arizona=E2=80=99s <b>Eli Crane</b> and Flo=
rida=E2=80=99s <b>Matt Gaetz</b>, although those late-summer primaries have=
n=E2=80=99t developed enough to draw any firm conclusions. </li><br/><li><i=
>Moderates under fire</i>: Right-wing groups are also on the hunt to take o=
ut some incumbents this cycle. The biggest race is on Tuesday, when
second-term Texan <b>Tony Gonzales</b> faces conservative rival <b>Brandon<=
/b> <b>Herrera</b>. Gonzales is an incredibly savvy campaigner, and he and =
his allies have outspent the opposition by <i>millions</i>. Even so, a numb=
er of G.O.P. strategists are nervous. <br/><br/>Meanwhile, newly installed =
House Approps chairman <b>Tom Cole</b> is running as if his career depends =
on it. The longtime Oklahoma congressman and his super PAC allies are spend=
ing big on his June 18 primary, even though most strategists think he=E2=80=
=99ll be fine. There are some frustrations surrounding the Approps chair ha=
ving to spend money on his own reelection rather than fundraising for the N=
=2ER.C.C. Other incumbents to watch:=
 Utah=E2=80=99s <b>Celeste Maloy</b> (Jun=
e 25), South Carolina=E2=80=99s <b>William Timmons</b> (June 20), Washingto=
n State=E2=80=99s <b>Dan Newhouse</b>, and Florida=E2=80=99s <b>Dan Webster=
</b> (both on August 20).</li><br/><li><i>The anti-Israel wave</i>: A handf=
ul of Squad members are facing challenges
from the pro-Israel side of the Democratic Party. <b>Jamaal Bowman</b>=E2=
=80=99s reelection bid in New York is the talk of the political class: He=
=E2=80=99s running a well-funded campaign, but AIPAC-supported rival <b>Geo=
rge Latimer</b> has outraised him and has serious support coming in from ou=
tside groups. <br/><br/>Meanwhile, Missouri=E2=80=99s <b>Cori Bush</b> has =
fundraised at a similar clip as <b>Wesley Bell</b>, her Democratic opponent=
, but her burn rate has given Bell a meaningful cash-on-hand advantage in t=
he August 6 primary. In Minnesota, <b>Ilhan Omar</b> is again facing <b>Don=
 Samuels</b>, who nearly toppled her two years ago, but the three-term cong=
resswoman recently won the state party=E2=80=99s endorsement and has only e=
xpanded her already strong fundraising machine.<br/><br/></li><li><i>The ou=
tliers</i>: And then there are a pair of races that don=E2=80=99t fit neatl=
y into larger political trends. Louisiana Republican <b>Garret Graves </b>d=
rew the short end of the stick during
Louisiana=E2=80=99s redistricting, and his fellow Louisianan <b>Mike Johnso=
n </b><u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1l=
